[1] Case update
- 6 Jun 2018. Epidemiological situation 5 Jun 2018, DRC Ministry of Health [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=8e6ccd9518

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 5 Jun 2018:
- a total of 60 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, including 37 confirmed, 14 probable, and 9 suspected;
- 6 new suspected cases, including 2 in Bikoro, 3 in Iboko, and 1 in Wangata. Three of these cases are known contacts;
- 4 samples were negative;
- no deaths reported today [total of 27 deaths; 13 of them among the confirmed cases];
- no new cases confirmed today.

Epidemiological analyzes have identified contacts living in nearby health areas in Bikoro and Iboko. These contacts are followed and advised to limit their movements during the entire follow-up period of 21 days.

Remarks
- Negative tests are systematically removed from the summary table.
- The category of probable cases includes all reported deaths for which it was not possible to obtain biological samples for laboratory confirmation.

News from the Ebola response
Vaccination
- Since the launch of the vaccination on [21 May 2018], 1579 people have been vaccinated, including 622 in Mbandaka, 372 in Bikoro, 555 in Iboko, and 30 in Ingende.

Sensitization
- This Wed 6 Jun 2018, teams of communicators from the Ministry of Health, WHO, and UNICEF organized an awareness session for 50 traditional healers (traditional doctors) of the city of Mbandaka. During this session, they discussed the generalities of Ebola virus disease as well as the prevention methods and the hygiene measures to respect in order to stop the transmission of the virus.
- These traditional doctors or healers are an important target for awareness because they are the first resort of the inhabitants when they are sick. It is therefore essential for the Ministry of Health to work with these healers so that they can spread the good messages to the people and invite them to adopt more responsible behaviors.
- At the beginning of the session, the healers were invited to share their opinion on the Ebola virus disease. Many of them said that it was not a real disease but rather a curse of ancestors that could be broken through traditional remedies.
- However, the session was successful and the traditional healers were convinced by the messages of health communicators. They are committed to the recommended hygiene measures, such as the use of gloves during consultations.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[It is critical that the traditional healers understand how Ebola virus is transmitted so they too can become involved in the control of virus spread. The people are much more likely to follow the guidance provided by the healers than that from foreign healthcare workers.
Of the 6 new cases, only 3 are reported as being contacts. We can only hope the other 3 are not part of new transmission chains. - Mod.LK]

- 6 Jun 2018. Ebola outbreak appears to be slowing in Congo as vaccines spread
[The Hill, edited]
http://thehill.com/policy/international/391003-ebola-outbreak-appears-to-be-slowing-in-congo-as-vaccines-spread
[byline: Reid Wilson]

Early signs suggest that an Ebola outbreak in Congo, which has killed 27 people since erupting in a remote rural village 2 months ago, is being contained before it can spread further.

A total of 58 suspected or confirmed cases have been documented in the Equateur province, a few hundred miles up the Congo River from the capital, Kinshasa. In recent days, 2 more victims have died, and 5 new suspected cases -- all of whom had contact with someone else with the virus -- have been identified.

The outbreak began in the small village of Ikoko Impenge, then spread to the lakeside town Bikoro before arriving in Mbandaka, a city of more than a million residents on the Congo River.

The latest situation report from the World Health Organization (WHO) said the last confirmed case was identified on 28 May [2018]. Peter Salama, the WHO's deputy director general for emergency preparedness and response, said on Twitter early [Wed 6 Jun 2018] that the number of cases had grown to 58.

The current eruption is the first to test a new vaccine, which appeared effective in Guinea late in 2015.

The 1st doses of the vaccine arrived in the 3 Congolese cities on 21 May [2018], and in the following 2 weeks about 1200 people have received the drug, WHO said.

Front-line health workers, those most at risk of coming into contact with a victim of the Ebola virus, are the first to receive the vaccine. The 2nd priority is those who have come into contact with an Ebola victim, and those with whom they in turn have been in contact with -- a practice known as ring vaccination -- used to stop the spread of a virus.

Guinean doctors who helped deploy the vaccine in their home country have spent weeks in the hot zone administering the drug. Still, health officials are worried about the virus spreading outside the Equateur province. The Congolese government and WHO have identified 115 possible points of entry and exit from the province and Kinshasa, setting up special screening measures at airports in Mbandaka and Kinshasa.

Partner organizations and governments have already raced about USD 25 million to the region for a rapid response, aimed at containing the virus before it spreads to other cities up and down the Congo River. The US Agency for International Development has contributed about USD 5.3 million of that total, and governments in the United Kingdom, Germany, Norway, Canada, and Italy have also chipped in. WHO has said a full-scale response could cost up to USD 57 million.

Teams from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, which maintains a satellite office in Kinshasa, have been sent to Mbandaka and Bikoro to help with the response. More than 170 WHO experts have been sent to the 3 epicenters of the outbreak, and Doctors Without Borders [Médecins sans Frontières; MSF] is operating isolation facilities in Mbandaka and Bikoro. The group is building 2 more Ebola treatment centers in the towns of Iboko and Itipo.

The Ebola virus can incubate in a human body for up to 21 days before a person shows any symptoms. Once a virus has been identified, a country must make it 2 successive incubation periods -- 42 days -- without a new case before being declared free of the Ebola virus.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

[The number of points of entry and exit cited from the province and Kinshasa -- 115 -- is probably a low estimate of the number of possible locations of transit an individual could use. How to control those points that are not official points of entry/exit is a challenge. See report from the International Organization for Migration (IOM) below for more on monitoring points of entry.
A further challenge is the number of days Ebola virus can incubate in the body, that is, 21, before symptoms are evident. The question is whether the infected individual is silently infectious during the incubation period. -Mod.LK]

- 5 Jun 2018. [data as reported by 3 Jun 2018]. Ebola virus disease - Democratic Republic of Congo, WHO external situation report 8
[WHO Health Emergency Information and Risk Assessment, edited]
http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/272761/SITREP-EVD-DRC-20180605-eng.pdf

The outbreak of Ebola virus disease (EVD) in the Democratic Republic of the Congo remains active. On 3 Jun 2018, 6 new suspected EVD cases have been reported in Bikoro (5) and Wangata (1) health zones. 3 laboratory specimens (from suspected cases reported on 2 Jun 2018) tested negative. No new confirmed EVD cases and no new deaths have been reported since our last situation update on 1 Jun 2018.

Since the beginning of the outbreak (on 4 Apr 2018), a total of 56 EVD cases and 25 deaths (case fatality rate 44.6 per cent) have been reported, as of 3 Jun 2018. Of the 56 cases, 37 have been laboratory confirmed, 13 are probable (deaths for which it was not possible to collect laboratory specimens for testing), and 6 are suspected. Of the confirmed and probable cases, 25 (50 per cent) are from Iboko, followed by 21 (42 per cent) from Bikoro and four (8 per cent) from Wangata health zones. A total of 5 healthcare workers have been affected, with 4 confirmed cases and 2 deaths.

The outbreak has remained localised to the 3 health zones initially affected: Iboko (23 confirmed cases, 2 probable, 5 deaths), Bikoro (10 confirmed cases, 11 probable, 5 suspected, 17 deaths), and Wangata (4 confirmed cases, 1 suspected, 3 deaths). As of 31 May 2018, a total of 880 contacts remain under active follow-up.

--
